assessment_title: Tag image file format for image technology (TIFF/IT)
scenario_purpose: The European Interoperability Framework(EIF) provides guidance to public administrations on how to improve governance of their interoperability activities, establish cross-organisational relationships, streamline processes supporting end-to-end digital services, and ensure that existing and new legislation do not compromise interoperability efforts.This CAMSS Scenario allows to assess the compliance of interoperability specifications with the EIF. The objective of the obtained assessment is to determine the suitability of the assessed interoperability specification for the delivery of interoperable European public services.
P1: Tag image file format for image technology (TIFF/IT)
criterion_description: The specification has been included in a national catalogue from a Member State whose NIF is fully aligned with at least 4 out of 5 sections of the EIF according to NIFO factsheets.
statement:
TIFF/IT is included in 2 national catalogues of recommended specifications. They belong to Estonia and Spain.
The National Interoperability Framework (NIF) of these Member States is fully aligned with at least 4 out of 5 sections of the European Interoperability Framework (EIF) according to the National Interoperability Framework Observatory (NIFO) factsheets. 

National catalogue Estonia: 
https://www.mkm.ee/sites/default/files/interoperability-framework_2011.doc

National catalogue Spain:
https://administracionelectronica.gob.es/pae_Home/pae_Estrategias/pae_Interoperabilidad_Inicio/pae_Normas_tecnicas_de_interoperabilidad.html#CATALOGOESTANDARES

NIFO factsheets:
https://joinup.ec.europa.eu/collection/national-interoperability-framework-observatory-nifo/nifo-factsheets

assessment_title: Tag image file format for image technology (TIFF/IT)
scenario_purpose: The European Interoperability Framework(EIF) provides guidance to public administrations on how to improve governance of their interoperability activities, establish cross-organisational relationships, streamline processes supporting end-to-end digital services, and ensure that existing and new legislation do not compromise interoperability efforts.This CAMSS Scenario allows to assess the compliance of interoperability specifications with the EIF. The objective of the obtained assessment is to determine the suitability of the assessed interoperability specification for the delivery of interoperable European public services.
P1: Tag image file format for image technology (TIFF/IT)
criterion_description: The specification facilitates the publication of public data as open data.
statement:
TIFF/IT is high quality image format, it is used to send data for print-ready pages that have been designed on high-end prepress systems. Also, it uses lossless compression.
Although the specification complies with the first level of maturity of Tom Berners-Lee's 5-star schema for Open data, it is not enough to consider TIFF/IT as an asset to facilitate the publication of open data.

Tim Berners-Lee 5-star schema for Open Data:
https://5stardata.info/es/ 

TIFF/IT ISO reference:
https://www.iso.org/standard/34342.html

P1: Tag image file format for image technology (TIFF/IT)
criterion_description: All stakeholders have the opportunity to contribute to the development of the specification
statement:
ISO has defined a clear procedure to develop its standards. It consists in a 6-steps process where everyone who is interested can participate. However, if you want to participate, you have to contact your national standards body and you have to be approved for joining the Technical committee (TC) who will develop the standard. ISO has defined the roadmap of standards, it is composed of 6 steps as before said. For the approval of a standard the two-thirds majority of P-members of TC is needed. If the result is negative, the document is returned to TC/SC to be further studied.

The ISO standardization process: 
https://www.iso.org/stages-and-resources-for-standards-development.html

criterion_description: A public review is part of the decision-making process.
statement:
As defined on the TC standardisation, only TC members are involved in the development of ISO standards. A review is carried out to arrange the consensus firstly within the TC members and subsequently is reviewed by the different ISO member bodies. However, it cannot be considered a public review, because only TC members can participate.

https://www.iso.org/stages-and-resources-for-standards-development.html

P1: Tag image file format for image technology (TIFF/IT)
criterion_description: The specification is sufficiently mature for its use in the development of products and services.
statement:
TIFF/IT was released in 1996 as a standard for the exchange of digital adverts. It became an ISO standard in 1998 as ISO 12639:1998, the specification had some modifications and the current version was published in 2004. The last review of TIFF/IT was in 2017 and it was confirmed to be the latest version. So it is clear that the specification is mature enough for develop of products and services.

TIFF/IT ISO reference:
https://www.iso.org/standard/34342.html

P1: Tag image file format for image technology (TIFF/IT)
criterion_description: The specification has sufficient market acceptance for its use in the development of products and services.
statement:
TIFF/IT is mainly used to store bitmap images that they will be intended to edit. TIFF/IT uses lossless compression, maintaining original quality while reducing in size. However, PSD extension is getting popular to store high quality images for later editing. It uses lossless compression as TIFF/IT and it is supported by any application.

TIFF Image file explanation:
https://www.canto.com/blog/tiff-image-file/

P1: Tag image file format for image technology (TIFF/IT)
criterion_description: The specification fosters the secure and trustworthy data exchange between citizens and businesses, and public administrations.
statement:
TIFF/IT is one of the safest image file types available. The most important security benefit is the transparent data of every TIFF image file. This fact makes possible to evaluate the information about the photo before opening and it prevents the chance of a virus hiding in the file. So the specification makes data exchange between citizens and public administrations secure and trustworthy.

scenario_purpose: The European Interoperability Framework(EIF) provides guidance to public administrations on how to improve governance of their interoperability activities, establish cross-organisational relationships, streamline processes supporting end-to-end digital services, and ensure that existing and new legislation do not compromise interoperability efforts.This CAMSS Scenario allows to assess the compliance of interoperability specifications with the EIF. The objective of the obtained assessment is to determine the suitability of the assessed interoperability specification for the delivery of interoperable European public services.
P1: Tag image file format for image technology (TIFF/IT)
criterion_description: The specification is recommended by an EU Member State.
statement:
8 Member States are recommending TIFF in their ICT National Catalogues. This Member States are Estonia, France, Germany, Greece, Norway, Poland, Slovenia and Spain.

assessment_title: Tag image file format for image technology (TIFF/IT)
scenario_purpose: The European Interoperability Framework(EIF) provides guidance to public administrations on how to improve governance of their interoperability activities, establish cross-organisational relationships, streamline processes supporting end-to-end digital services, and ensure that existing and new legislation do not compromise interoperability efforts.This CAMSS Scenario allows to assess the compliance of interoperability specifications with the EIF. The objective of the obtained assessment is to determine the suitability of the assessed interoperability specification for the delivery of interoperable European public services.
P1: Tag image file format for image technology (TIFF/IT)
criterion_description: The specification has been selected for its use in an EU cross-border project or initiative after agreed identification and assessment.
statement:
Although no formal agreements have been found on the usage of TIFF, there are different projects and initiatives at European level, that use TIFF files for the data exchange. Some examples of Agencies and projects involving the specification are the European Environment Agency and its Evaluation map of Europe, which is available on TIFF format. Also, the initiative founded by the European Commission, OpenAire, which is aimed to foster cooperation among researchers over Europe and the discoverability of their data. This initiative defines guidelines for data management in the context of H2020 Programme: Guidelines on FAIR Data Management in Horizon 2020.

OpenAire Preservation Guidelines:
https://www.openaire.eu/data-formats-preservation-guide

Elevation Map of Europe:
https://www.eea.europa.eu/data-and-maps/data/digital-elevation-model-of-europe

Digital Elevation Model over Europe:
https://www.eea.europa.eu/data-and-maps/data/eu-dem

P1: Tag image file format for image technology (TIFF/IT)
criterion_description: The specification fosters the publication of data as Linked Open Data.
statement:
Although TIFF/IT supports the first level of maturity from the Tim Berners-Lee 5-star schema for the Open data, it does not support the main principles for the publication of data as Linked Open Data.

5-star linked open data:
https://www.w3.org/DesignIssues/LinkedData.html
https://www.w3.org/wiki/LinkedData
